      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan amortization table and i'm confused. i've been making the same monthly payment for a year now but the principal balance is barely moving. why is the balance decreasing so slowly even though i'm paying the same amount every month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a classic case of the \"Goblin Math\" trap, where the interest rate is a mischievous goblin that eats up your hard-earned coins before you can even see the principal balance tick down.\n\nWhen you make that same monthly payment, the first few months are mostly just feeding the interest goblin. The goblin is very hungry in the beginning, so it claims almost all of your payment just to stay alive, leaving only a tiny fraction to actually chip away at the principal. It's like trying to build a tower of blocks while a giant goblin is constantly knocking them over; you have to work twice as hard just to make a single step forward.\n\nAs time goes on and the balance gets smaller, the goblin gets a bit less hungry, and suddenly you'll notice your principal balance moving faster. But right now, you are just in the slow, grinding phase where the goblin is hoarding your money. Don't worry, the goblin is just waiting for you to pay down the debt enough so it can finally stop eating your savings and start letting you build your future.",
