      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your frustration, and I apologize for the excessive goblin metaphors earlier; I will keep the actual math clear and direct this time.\n\nThe reason your principal balance moves so slowly is due to how interest is calculated on the **remaining balance**.\n\nHere is the step-by-step calculation for a standard amortization schedule:\n\n1.  **Calculate Monthly Interest:** The lender takes your current principal balance and multiplies it by your annual interest rate (divided by 12 for the monthly rate).\n    *   *Formula:* `Current Balance × (Annual Rate / 12) = Monthly Interest`\n2.  **Determine Principal Payment:** You subtract that calculated interest from your fixed monthly payment.\n    *   *Formula:* `Fixed Payment - Monthly Interest = Principal Paid`\n3.  **Update Balance:** You subtract the principal paid from the current balance.\n    *   *Formula:* `Current Balance - Principal Paid = New Balance`\n\nIn the early years of a loan, the balance is high, so the \"Monthly Interest\" step results in a large number. This large interest amount eats up most of your fixed payment, leaving very little money to reduce the principal. As the balance",
